79. Some observations on Trees.

i. Let T is a tree with n >= 3 vertices.

Suppose we have to choose 3 distinct vertices x, y and z such that the number of unique edges on the simple paths between x and y, y and z, and, z and x is the maximum.

Then, it is optimal to do the following:

Select two diameter nodes of the tree x, y.
Then, from all the nodes on the diameter path x-y, run a multi-source BFS and update and dist array accordingly. The third vertex z should be such that z != x, y and dist[z] >= dist[v] for all nodes v in T.

ii. Let T is a tree with n vertices.
Let some vertices of the tree be marked.

Let f(v) = maximum distance from node v to any of the marked nodes.

Suppose we have to find the minimum value of f(v) for all vertices v of T.

Let one of the marked nodes be the root of T.

To do this, create a modified tree such that the only difference between this new tree and T is that only the nodes and edges on the path from root to the marked nodes are included in the tree.

The answer then is the radius of this new tree.

80. Subtree DP

Subtree DP processes trees from leaves to root. You compute values for leaf nodes first, then use those to compute values for their parents, and so on up to the root.

The pattern:

dp[node] = f(dp[child_1], dp[child_2], ...)

You combine child answers to get the parent answers.

This works because trees have no cycles, each node depends only on descendants.

Use DFS with post-order processing. Visit children before processing the current node. This ensures you have all child results before computing the parent's result.

The recursion naturally handles the tree structure. Post-order means you work from leaves up to the root. This bottom-up flow is the essence of subtree DP.

Use subtree DP when:

1. The input is a tree (acyclic, connected graph).

2. The problem asks for something aggregated (count, max, sum) over nodes or subtrees.

3. The answer for a node depends only on its descendants, not ancestors.

If you see these patterns, the approach is: define state on nodes, write recurrence combining children, implement DFS with post-order traversal. This structure solves most tree DP problems.

i. Define clearly what dp[node] represents. It should be something like "... for the subtree rooted at node". This value should be returned by dfs(node).

ii. An unrooted tree has no designated root. To use subtree DP, pick any node as root (often node 1). Once rooted, edges have direction (parent to child). Subtrees are well-defined. 

Some problems care about the root choice (path queries). Others do not (subtree sizes). The choice of root changes which nodes are ancestors v/s descendants, but not the tree structure itself.

iii. Core pattern: define state, write the recurrence, handle the base case of the leaf nodes, implement DFS.

iv. Some problems need two DP values per node: one if you include the node in the solution, one if you exclude it.

Transitions depend on whether you include or exclude each node. The constraint (eg, cannot pick adjacent nodes) determines how you combine child values.

When its needed to calculate multiple values per node, return a tuple of all those values from the DFS. This eliminates the need for a DP table.

v. Some problems ask for the best path in a tree. A path is a sequence of nodes connected by edges.

Core Idea: Every path has a highest node (turning point) (the path closest to the root that is on the path). All the other nodes on the path are in the subtree of this turning point. The turning point v of a path breaks it into two parts: the path goes up to v from one of the childsubtrees of v and may continue into some other child subtree of v.

Consider each node as a potential highest node and base your DP on this, i.e, dp[node] = "... for paths having node as their turning point." Such paths lie entirely in the subtree rooted at node.

For node v, the best path having v as its turning point combines the best paths going down into its different child subtrees. You pick the two best downwards paths and connect them through v, forming a path that has a turning point at v.

Many tree path problems need two values: one for the global answer (path through node), one for recursion (path extending from node). The returned value is what the parent uses to extend its own path. The global variable tracks the overall best path found.

87. Counting number of unique elements with a Segment Tree

If the values in the array lie in a small bounded range such as 0 ≤ v ≤ 63, we can efficiently maintain the number of distinct elements in any segment using a segment tree with bitmasks. Instead of storing frequencies, each node stores a 64-bit integer mask representing which values appear in its segment. The i-th bit of the mask is set if the value i occurs at least once in that segment.

For a leaf node corresponding to element a[i], the mask is simply (1 << a[i]). For an internal node, the mask is computed as the bitwise OR of the masks of its two children, because a value appears in the parent segment if it appears in either child.

To answer a query for a range [l, r], we combine the masks of the segment tree nodes that cover the range using bitwise OR. The resulting mask represents all values present in that range. The number of unique elements is then obtained by counting the number of set bits (popcount) in the final mask.

Point updates are handled by updating the mask at the leaf and recomputing masks along the path to the root using OR. Since each node stores only a fixed-size 64-bit mask, both queries and updates run in O(log n) time with very small constant factors.

Range updates are a bit trickier to handle and I've done a question regarding this in random/newYearTree.cpp

