89. Some Observations regarding Euler Tour of a Tree and LCA

i. Distance Formula using LCA

Let T be a tree rooted at node x.
For any two nodes u and v:

    dist(u, v) = depth(u) + depth(v) - 2 * depth(lca(u, v))

Explanation:

The path from u to v goes through their Lowest Common Ancestor.
The path can be decomposed as: u → lca(u, v) → v

Now,
    dist(u, lca) = depth(u) - depth(lca)
    dist(v, lca) = depth(v) - depth(lca)

Therefore,
    dist(u, v)
    = dist(u, lca) + dist(v, lca)
    = (depth(u) - depth(lca)) + (depth(v) - depth(lca))
    = depth(u) + depth(v) - 2 * depth(lca)

Thus if we know the depth of every node and can compute LCA quickly, we can compute distances in O(1).
Depths can be precomputed with a single DFS/BFS in O(N).

---------------------------------------------------------------------

ii. Euler Tour Flattening of a Tree

Let T be a rooted tree with root x and N >= 1 nodes.

A DFS traversal of the tree can be used to flatten the tree into an array.
This process is called an Euler Tour.

Flattening is useful because many complex hierarchical tree problems can then be converted into simple range problems on 1D arrays, which can be solved using Segment Trees, Fenwick Trees (BIT), Sparse Tables, etc.

An Euler Tour can be constructed in O(N).

---------------------------------------------------------------------

iii. Euler Tour Type 1 — Entry Time Only (Size N)

During DFS, record the timer when we first visit a node.
Timer increments exactly once per node.

    in[v] = timer++

We also maintain the out-time (when we finish the subtree):
    out[v] = timer - 1

Property:
Then every node in the subtree of v will occupy a contiguous segment:
    [ in[v], out[v] ]

Why this works:
DFS completely processes a node's subtree before returning to its parent.
Therefore all nodes of a subtree appear consecutively in the DFS order.

Uses:
• Subtree sum/minimum/maximum queries
• Subtree updates
• Counting nodes in a subtree with specific properties
• Maintaining subtree information with Segment Trees or Fenwick Trees

---------------------------------------------------------------------

iv. Euler Tour Type 2 — Entry and Exit Times (Size 2N)

During DFS, the timer increments when we enter AND when we exit a node.
Each node is pushed to an array E of size 2N twice.

    start[v] = ++timer
    E[timer]  = v
    // process children
    end[v]   = ++timer
    E[timer]  = v

Invariants & Properties:

1. Ancestor Relationship:
    u is an ancestor of v  <=>  start[u] <= start[v] <= end[u]

2. The Cancellation Trick (Path Sums):
    If we want to query path sums, we map values to a flattened array A:
        A[start[x]] =  value[x]
        A[end[x]]   = -value[x]

3. Root-to-Node Path Queries:
    The prefix sum of A from 1 to start[v] gives the exact sum of values on the path from the root to v.
    Why? Because any node x that is NOT on the path to v (i.e., it was visited but we already exited its subtree) will have both A[start[x]] and A[end[x]] included in the prefix sum. They cancel out (+value - value = 0). Only the nodes currently "open" (ancestors of v) contribute to the sum.

4. Ancestor-to-Descendant Path Queries:
    If u is an ancestor of v, the range sum of A from [start[u], start[v]] gives the path sum from u to v.
    Why? All nodes visited between entering u and entering v (that are not on the direct path) are fully explored subtrees. They appear twice in this range (entry and exit) and cancel to 0. 

5. Node-to-Node Path Queries (General Case):
    If u is NOT an ancestor of v (assume start[u] < start[v]):
    The range sum of A from [end[u], start[v]] leaves EXACTLY the path from u to v, EXCEPT for their LCA.
    Why? Moving from end[u] to start[v], we go up the tree and back down. Subtrees fully explored between them cancel out. However, the LCA(u, v) encloses both, so its start time is BEFORE start[u], meaning it is completely excluded from the range [end[u], start[v]].
    Path Sum = RangeSum(A, end[u], start[v]) + value[LCA(u, v)]

Uses:
• Point updates and Path sum queries in O(log N) using a Fenwick/Segment Tree.
• Checking ancestor relationships in O(1).
• Path tricks, tree difference arrays, and offline queries involving paths.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

v. Euler Tour Type 3 — Full Euler Tour (Used for LCA, Size 2N-1)

In this version we record every time a node is visited during DFS.
When DFS moves parent -> child OR child -> parent, we log the node.

Example:
Tree: 1 -> 2 -> 4, 1 -> 3
Euler tour: 1 2 4 2 1 3 1

We record:
    first[v] = first position of v in the Euler array
    depth[]  = the depth of the node at each step of the tour

Observation:
The LCA of u and v is the node with the minimum depth in the Euler tour segment:
    [ min(first[u], first[v]), max(first[u], first[v]) ]

Proof idea:
During DFS, when we move from u to v in the traversal, we must pass through their LCA. The highest point (minimum depth) reached between visiting u and v is exactly the LCA. 

By building a Sparse Table over the depth array:
    Precomputation:  O(N log N)
    Query:           O(1)

This successfully reduces LCA queries to a standard Range Minimum Query (RMQ).

---------------------------------------------------------------------

vi. Summary of Euler Tour Variants

1. Entry Time Only (Size N array)
    Purpose: Subtree queries and Subtree updates.
    Key property: subtree(v) -> contiguous segment in DFS order.
    Common tools: Segment Tree / Fenwick Tree.

2. Entry + Exit Times (Size 2N array)
    Purpose: Path sum queries, Point updates on paths, Ancestor checks.
    Key property: Nodes not on the path appear twice and cancel out (+val, -val).
    Common tools: Fenwick Tree (BIT), Prefix Sums.

3. Full Euler Tour (Size 2N-1 array)
    Purpose: Fast O(1) LCA queries.
    Key idea: LCA becomes RMQ over the depth array.
    Common tools: Sparse Table.

---------------------------------------------------------------------

Key Insight

The main power of the Euler Tour is that it converts non-linear hierarchical tree structures into linear 1D arrays. 
By strategically defining WHEN we write to the array (Entry, Exit, or Every Visit) and WHAT we write (Values, Cancelled Values, or Depths), difficult tree routing problems are reduced to standard array range queries.